posts.cooked:
Hi guys,

For the last couple of months we’ve been designing and prototyping our custom swerve. Today we’d like to share our work with you.

https://github.com/Rabyte-association/Rabyte_Swerve_Module

Basic characteristics of our module:

as metric as possible

using NEOs for both driving and steering

using Redux HELIUM Canandcoders

custom polyurethane cast wheels with PLA cores

30x60mm profiles for frame

some 3D printed parts

gears are modified off-the-shelf metric gears

7:64 steering ratio

1:7 or 4:21 drive ratio (1 gear swap)

the design is based on the SDS mk4

How do you like it? Do you have any suggenstions? We’d be happy to hear your thoughts.

Looks really good!  Here are some quick thoughts:

I like the 1.5mm thick retaining plates for the x-contact bearing.  If they prove to be undersized, you can easily thicken them up. image 869×567 57 KB

I like the 1.5mm thick retaining plates for the x-contact bearing.  If they prove to be undersized, you can easily thicken them up. image 869×567 57 KB

image 869×567 57 KB

image 869×567 57 KB

The steering ratio seems a little fast to me.  Yours is ~9:1, whereas the Mk4i is ~21:1.  You might consider a smaller motor pinion, or moving the motor (and intermediate shaft) so that you can fit a bigger gear above the small pulley? image 649×598 45.2 KB

The steering ratio seems a little fast to me.  Yours is ~9:1, whereas the Mk4i is ~21:1.  You might consider a smaller motor pinion, or moving the motor (and intermediate shaft) so that you can fit a bigger gear above the small pulley? image 649×598 45.2 KB

image 649×598 45.2 KB

image 649×598 45.2 KB

speaking of the small steering pulley, you will need a thinner one, or a taller large pulley.  Right now the steering belt can walk off of the top of the large pulley.   Consider going taller if you can - I know the Mk3s has problems with 9mm thick steering belts breaking (although the small pulleys there have much fewer teeth) image 709×474 40.4 KB

Is there a good reason for the milled corner insert?  It seems to me a bottom plate like the Mk4i would do the same job with less weight and cost.  Yours looks really good though! image 800×615 54.4 KB

I would advise not putting all of your eggs in one basket and looking for a COTS option if you can (although I know that is a different cost-value decision from Poland) image 700×567 72.5 KB

I’d consider making the axle bolt go all the way through a hollow axle, rather than be fastened by screws on either side.  One of those screws is always going to want to unscrew on you.  You can make it work with loctite.   That’s easily changed in future if you want to chance it. image 858×563 94.6 KB

Speaking of the way the wheel attaches. you might consider flipping the bolts that secure the fork to the steering pulley.  Right now, if you want to change a wheel, you have to loosen those bolts from above, where they are obstructed by the motors.  That could be a headache. image 844×604 57.3 KB

Overall though, it’s a pretty solid design.   Congrats! Hopefully you find it quick to build because the current rules really don’t favour building your own.  Other teams will be able to use their pre-assembled Mk4 modules from a previous year while you will have to remachine all of this every year .

posts.cooked:
Another catch - I think you want to rethink how the bearings for the steering intermediate shaft are supported.  The top bearing is going to rub against the motor unless you add some kind of spacer around the OD.  Also the bottom pulley is going to rub on the bottom plates unless you add a thicker spacer on the ID there. image 506×569 60.5 KB

image 506×569 60.5 KB

image 506×569 60.5 KB

Compared to the SDS modules there’s one huge win here, and that’s the bigger steering pulley that helps save steering belts.

We’ve had issues with belt breakage because of the tooth engagement on our MK4i driving pulleys - those pulleys have many fewer teeth and as a result they stress the belt more unevenly and cause breakage eventually. While not a major problem, it’s still a failure point that this design should all but do away with.

posts.cooked:
andrzej:

custom polyurethane cast wheels with PLA cores

Any reason you decided to go with PLA cores? PLA can be extremely strong no doubt. But it’s very bad at impact strength. You might find picking ABS or a similar strong and impact resistant material more effective.

Huge thanks for all ideas. For the corner insert we planned for it to be 3d printed, and use the bellypan for structual support on the bottom. Thread on the weheels is casted poliurethane, we did some tests and the resoults are promising.
We decded on PLA, beasouse its easiest to print (we are still working on our setup), we might consider switching to PCTG or policarbonate or ABS like you suggest.
